    {{#> case/paragraphe title="The challenge" }}
        <p>15% of H&M online customers are not members of the loyalty program.
            How might we encourage them to sign up?</p>
    {{/case/paragraphe}}

    {{#> case/paragraphe title="My role" }}
        <p><strong>Product Designer</strong> in a Team in charge of increasing the number of sign ups. The team hadn't
            had a Product Designer before.
        </p>
    {{/case/paragraphe}}

    {{#> case/paragraphe title="The process" }}
        <p>We were bombarded with requests to add more features, or put the sign up button
            in more places. But there was little data to back that up! So, I conducted research
            to help us decide what to prioritise.</p>

    {{/case/paragraphe}}

    {{#> case/twoColumn }}
        {{#> case/leftColumn title="Research" img="img/hm1_signup_Clicktale.png"
                             alt="21% drop out at the date of birth. Drop out is much lower for other fields (3 to 4%)" }}
            On mobile, the drop out rate during sign up was high, mostly due to the date of birth field (screenshot
            from
            Clicktale).


        {{/case/leftColumn}}
        {{#> case/rightColumn}}
            <h4>Research questions</h4>
            <ul>
                <li>Are there issues stopping users from signing up?</li>
                <li>Can users find where to sign up? Are we promoting sign up right?</li>
                <li>Are there market specificities we should be aware of?</li>
            </ul>
            <h4>Methodologies used</h4>
            <ul>
                <li>Click tests on <a href="https://www.userzoom.com/">Userzoom</a>.</li>
                <li>User testing.</li>
                <li>Review existing in-house research into country specifics.
                </li>
                <li>Gather quantitative data from <a
                        href="https://analytics.google.com/analytics/">Google Analytics</a> and
                    <a
                            href="https://www.clicktale.com/">Clicktale.</a></li>
            </ul>
            <h4>Key takeaways</h4>
            <ul>
                <li>No need to go too heavy on the Sign ups CTAs. Users can find it already, and it's getting a bit too
                    much. Instead, we should think of
                    the right context to promote sign up, and review our copy.
                </li>
                <li>Drop out rates on mobile (which accounts for 70% of H&M's visitors) is 30% higher than on desktop:
                    no wonder when it takes 40s longer to sign up, and there's severe usability issues (especially on
                    Android).
                </li>
                <li>In some countries, we must provide more sign-up options.
                </li>
            </ul>

            <h4>Prioritise and communicate</h4>
            <figure>
                <img src="img/hm1_impacteffort.jpg"
                     alt="Impact effort matrix">
                <figcaption>Priority we established based on research:<br>
                    Make it easier to enter date of birth,<br>
                    Provide social sign up (at least in key markets),<br>
                    Work on how we promote membership in the checkout<br>
                </figcaption>
            </figure>

        {{/case/rightColumn}}
    {{/case/twoColumn}}



    {{#> case/twoColumn }}
        {{#> case/leftColumn title="Reduce friction" img="img/hm1_signup_android_test.png"
                             alt="Fingers hovering over a calendar to select date of birth" }}
            A participant in user test, unsure how to change her birth year in the date picker (on Android).
        {{/case/leftColumn}}
        {{#> case/rightColumn}}


            <h4>The problem</h4>
            <p>The date of birth was by far the biggest drop off point in the sign up form.
            </p>
            <h4>How might we solve it?</h4>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Stop to require the date of birth:</strong>
                    The Product Owner and I started discussions with our stakeholders:
                    Why do we need the date of birth? How else can we collect it? I prototyped
                    a few ideas to help kickstart things.
                </li>
                <li><strong>Change the input method</strong>: with a precise date so far back in the past, a calendar
                    (Android) or a
                    scrollable list (iOS) are not the most appropriate. I reviewed existing research and guidelines
                    (like
                    <a href="https://design-system.service.gov.uk/patterns/dates/#asking-for-memorable-dates">Research
                        by gov.uk</a> and <a href="https://material.io/components/date-pickers#mobile-pickers">Material
                        Design</a>) and sketched out two ideas.
                </li>
            </ul>
            <h4>Design review</h4>
            <p>I took the ideas to our daily Design Review.
                We decided on the solution that allowed to stick to existing components in our Design System: simple
                input, split in 3 fields (day, month, year), with
                one visible label.</p>
            <h4>A/B Test</h4>
            <p><strong>Drop outs and time to complete the form decreased.</strong>
                And the rate of errors when filling in the form did not significantly change like we could have
                feared. </p>
            <h4>Next?</h4>
            <p>Address the next big drop off points: unclear password rules and error messages.</p>

        {{/case/rightColumn}}
    {{/case/twoColumn}}

    {{#> case/twoColumn }}
        {{#> case/leftColumn
